    questionType: 'passage',
    passageText: `The electron transport chain (ETC) in the inner mitochondrial membrane couples electron transfer to the pumping of protons from the matrix into the intermembrane space (IMS), establishing the proton motive force (PMF) that drives ATP synthesis by Complex V (ATP synthase). Four multi-subunit complexes participate: Complex I (NADH dehydrogenase) oxidizes NADH and reduces ubiquinone (Q); Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase) oxidizes FADH₂ and also reduces Q; Complex III (cytochrome bc₁) oxidizes QH₂ and reduces cytochrome c; and Complex IV (cytochrome c oxidase) transfers electrons to O₂, forming H₂O.

Researchers studying mitochondrial dysfunction used three pharmacological agents: Compound R (rotenone), which binds the Q-binding site of Complex I and prevents NADH-driven electron entry into the chain; Compound A (antimycin A), which blocks the Qᵢ site of Complex III, preventing QH₂ oxidation; and Compound O (oligomycin), which inhibits the Fₒ subunit of Complex V, blocking proton return through ATP synthase.

To quantify effects, isolated rat liver mitochondria were incubated with each compound individually and in combination with excess ADP and inorganic phosphate. O₂ consumption rate, matrix NADH fluorescence (proxy for NADH accumulation), PMF (measured by membrane potential-sensitive dye), and ATP synthesis rate were recorded. The investigators also tested the effect of the uncoupler FCCP (which renders the inner mitochondrial membrane permeable to protons, collapsing the PMF) on each inhibited preparation.`,
