    explanation: 'Choice C is correct. A single-base deletion shifts the reading frame for all codons downstream of the deletion. Starting at codon 5 (the site of deletion), every codon from position 5 to 300 is read in the wrong frame — triplet groupings shift by one nucleotide, producing a completely different amino acid sequence from position 5 onward. The probability of encountering a premature stop codon (UAA, UAG, or UGA) in a random reading frame is approximately 3/64 per codon (~5%), so most frameshifts introduce a premature stop within tens of codons, producing a severely truncated, non-functional protein.',
    wrongAnswerExplanations: {
      A: 'A missense mutation is a POINT mutation (single-nucleotide substitution) that changes one codon to code for a different amino acid — affecting only that codon. A single-BASE DELETION is fundamentally different: it shifts the reading frame for ALL downstream codons, not just the one at the deletion site. Single-base deletions are frameshifts, not missense mutations.',
      B: 'A silent (synonymous) mutation changes a nucleotide without changing the amino acid (due to codon degeneracy). Silent mutations only occur with substitutions within a codon. A deletion changes the reading frame entirely — the concept of "same functional class" amino acid is irrelevant when the entire downstream sequence is scrambled by the frameshift.',
      D: 'The genetic code is degenerate (multiple codons per amino acid) but it does NOT compensate for insertions or deletions. Codons are read in strict non-overlapping triplets by the ribosome; a one-nucleotide deletion permanently shifts all downstream codon boundaries. The ribosome cannot "skip" or adjust for deletions without shifting the entire reading frame.',
    },
    teachingPoint: 'Frameshift mutations: insertions or deletions of non-multiples-of-3 nucleotides shift the reading frame for all downstream codons. Effects: (1) all downstream amino acids changed; (2) high probability of premature stop codon (UAA/UAG/UGA); (3) truncated, usually non-functional protein. Contrast with point mutations: substitution → at most one amino acid changes (missense) or no change (silent/synonymous) or premature stop (nonsense). Early frameshift (codon 5 of 300) affects 295/300 codons = near-total protein disruption.',
