    questionType: 'passage',
    passageText: `Receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) are transmembrane receptors with intrinsic kinase activity. The epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR), a member of the ErbB family, undergoes conformational change upon EGF binding, forming homodimers or heterodimers that facilitate trans-autophosphorylation of intracellular tyrosine residues. Phosphorylated tyrosines serve as docking sites for adaptor proteins such as Grb2, which recruits the guanine nucleotide exchange factor Sos to activate RAS, initiating the RAS-RAF-MEK-ERK cascade. Concurrently, EGFR autophosphorylation recruits PI3K via adaptors, converting PIP2 to PIP3 and activating PDK1 and Akt to promote cell survival and proliferation.

Activating mutations in EGFR occur in a subset of non-small-cell lung cancers. The L858R substitution in the kinase domain constitutively activates the receptor independent of ligand. First-generation EGFR inhibitors (e.g., erlotinib, gefitinib) compete with ATP at the kinase domain active site. A secondary T790M resistance mutation at the gatekeeper residue sterically blocks binding of first-generation inhibitors while preserving receptor kinase activity. Third-generation inhibitors are designed to covalently modify C797 and overcome T790M resistance.

Researchers engineered five cell lines from a common parental lung epithelial background (Table 1). All lines were grown in serum-free media and stimulated with 50 ng/mL EGF where indicated.`,
